<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-035-200 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 440 307</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Oct 14 1991 v13 n41 p39(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft plans SQL Server upgrade offer: will offer new buyersless expensive upgrade to Release 4.2 next year. (Microsoft Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mace, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft plans to promote its SQL Server 4.2 upgrade of thepopular SQL Server database engine by offering new purchasers ofthe current version a less expensive upgrade under a buyer'sassurance plan.andP;  The current SQL Server 1.11 for OS/2 release doesnot provide the improvements found in Sybase Corp's Release 4.01,which has been available for Unix and VMS platforms since 1990.andO;Microsoft's Release 4.2 for OS/2 will include most of Sybase'senhancements, including the Open Server application programminginterface and support for multiple languages.andP;  Sybase's productwill still have some unique features, such as multiprocessingsupport, that Microsoft will not implement.andP;  Microsoft's decisionto port Release 4.2 to OS/2 1.3 rather than the 32-bit OS/2 2.0has earned considerable criticism.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Marketing).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   SQL Server 4.2 (Data base management system) (Marketing).andO;Topic:     Marketing StrategyUpgradingPromotion of ProductPricing Policy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>